content.problemStatement:
In this lesson, we learned about how to write conditions and print anything based on those conditions.

In the last two problems, you may have also noticed that we can use as many `if` statements as we like. 
```javascript
var a = 1;

if(a == 1) {
    console.log("a is 1");
}
if (a < 5) {
    console.log("a is less than 5");
}

// Output:
// a is 1
// a is less than 5
```

When we want to stop checking for conditions as soon as a condition is true, then we use `else if` and `else`.
```javascript
var a = 1;

if (a == 1) {
    console.log("a is 1");
} else if(a < 5){
    console.log("a is less than 5");
} else {
    console.log("no sure about value of a");
}

// Output:
// a is 1
```

Let's solve some more problems around conditions, then we will learn how to combine multiple conditions in a single if statement using `&&` and `||` (logical operators).

